      "text": "# Solution Doc for Performant, Reliable, Secure Real Time Writes\n\n## Mission\nWe are building a patient events platform for real-time ingestion, de-identify on write, and make de-identified records queryable within 5 seconds p99 while enforcing logical referential constraints to PHI data.\n\n## Invariants\n### Invariant: Global Idempotency by event_id\n\n    Guarantee: For any caller-provided event_id, the system returns the same outcome on retry: same map_id, same assigned version (once committed), and a monotonic phase transition\n(QUEUED→COMMITTED→DEID_PERSISTED/DEID_DLQ).\n    If the same event_id is presented with a different payload than originally queued, the request is rejected (e.g., 409) and does not mutate state.\n    \n### Invariant: Atomic Phase-1 Commit\n\n    Guarantee: Transition to COMMITTED(version=v) occurs if and only if:\n            1. the authoritative mapping row is durably written/updated with current_version=v and relevant metadata, and\n            2. PHI record (phi_record_id, v) is durably written (immutable). No partial COMMITTED is visible to callers.\n    \n### Invariant: Monotonic Version Authority & Serialization\n\n    Guarantee: For each map_id, versions strictly increase; version assignment defines ingest-time order and PHI state mutations are applied in that order.\n\n### Invariant: PHI Commit Before De-ID Projection\n\n    Guarantee: A de-id projection for (deid_token, version=v) must not be emitted unless the mapping store indicates COMMITTED(version=v) and the PHI record (phi_record_id, v) exists.\n    \n### Invariant: De-identification Separation\n\n    Guarantee: De-ID records contain no direct identifiers. Linkage to PHI is via deid_token and privileged resolution only. Tokens are not derivable from PHI fields.\n    \n### Invariant: Idempotent De-ID Projection (Downstream of COMMITTED)\n\n    Guarantee: Phase 2 de-identification is triggered only after Phase 1 is COMMITTED and uses the authoritative (deid_token, version) emitted by the atomic commit path. De-ID writes are idempotent by key (deid_token, version): retries\nmust not create duplicates and must not overwrite an existing (deid_token, version) record.\n    \n### Invariant: Bounded De-ID Materialization\n\n    Guarantee: When de-id dependencies are healthy, DEID_PERSISTED is reached within 5 seconds p99 after admission / COMMITTED. Under degraded conditions, de-id materialization reaches DEID_PERSISTED within 15 minutes p99\nafter recovery; otherwise terminal DEID_DLQ is recorded.\n\n### Invariant: Long-Term PHI Version Retention\n\n    Guarantee: Because the PHI store is an authoritative system of record, all committed PHI versions (phi_record_id, version) are retained in immutable form for the legally required retention period (e.g., years), unless explicitly removed by a\ncompliant erasure process (which is out-of-scope for this design).\n    \n\n## In-Scope\n- Ingest supports create + update workflows with caller-provided event_id\n- Idempotency by event_id with conflict detection on payload mismatch\n- Mapping/tokenization + version assignment as authoritative\n- Phase-1 atomic commit (mapping version + PHI immutable write)\n- Phase-2 de-id materialization with retry + DLQ terminal state\n- p99 ≤ 5s to reach DEID_PERSISTED in healthy conditions\n- Privileged PHI resolution via deid_token (interface can be mocked)\n\n## Out-of-scope\n- Control Plane vs Data Plane Separation\n- Authorization Boundaries\n- Audit & immutability guarantees beyond the versioned append-only model\n- Cost showback\n- Full observability platform (dashboards/alerts), aside from minimal phase timestamps if needed\n- Multi-region active/active\n- Deletes / erasure\n- Rich query APIs for business analytics (“API query of the data”)\n\n## Assumptions\n- Caller must provide a globally unique event_id for each semantic write. Retries must reuse the same event_id; event_id reuse across distinct payloads is a client bug and results in a deterministic 409 Conflict.\n- The SLO measures time from admission/commit to data visibility in the de-id read API. Query execution latency itself is out-of-scope except to the extent it must be negligible for key-based reads.\n- Prototype-only: simulate PHI separation, no real compliance claims(encryption, key mgmt, access controls, audit logs)\n- This is a single tenant, single region(w/ replication capabilities), separate data endpoints for PHI vs De-identification records.\n- “Queryable” for this take-home means the de-id record exists and is readable by key\n- 325M people in Epic system with EHR - this system should match in size\n- (1 kafka partition manages 600,000Kb/minute)/(20kb messages)=30,000 messages/minute per partition max\n- event_id reuse across distinct payloads is considered a client bug and results in a deterministic 409 Conflict.\n    \n\n## Deployment Technology Choices\n\n| Component | Take-Home / Rancher (Helm) | Production Direction |\n|---|---|---|\n| Event Topic `patient-events` | **Kafka Topic** default retention w/ one partition ISR=1 | **Kafka Topic** (multi-broker, multi-AZ, partitions=34, ISR=3, retention=24hours, 800GB max partition size)  |\n| `map-id-pool` queue (ID pool) | **Queues for Kafka** topic with retention kept simple for the prototype | **Queues for Kafka** with bounded retention by size and continuous pool replenishment |\n| Stream processing | **Flink** jobs (Phase 1 coordinator, Phase 2 projector) | **Flink** with HA(2 job managers, 2 task managers(6 core machines)), state backend, blue/green upgrades  |\n| Authoritative token mapping (Phase 1) | **PostgreSQL** (single-region) | **CockroachDB** (multi-region async replication, 60GB storage across 16 nodes) |\n| Immutable PHI store | **PostgreSQL** append-only table keyed by `(phi_record_id, version)` | **Object storage** (S3/MinIO + multi-region) + **Apache Iceberg** for immutable versioned history and time travel |\n| Immutable De-ID store | **PostgreSQL** append-only table keyed by `(deid_token, version)` | **Object storage** (S3/MinIO + multi-region) + **Apache Iceberg** (same rationale as PHI) |\n| DLQ | Kafka DLQ Topic | Kafka DLQ topic (34 partitions, 1GB/partition, 24hour retention, ISR=3) Must hold 24 hours of data or 64GB(color,  char(32)+deid_token, UUID(16b))/day but must also match partition count of ingestion topic. |\n\nNotes:\n- The take-home minimizes components by using PostgreSQL for immutable stores and Kafka for both the event queue and the `map_id` queue.\n- In production, Apache Iceberg on object storage is the preferred direction for the immutable stores because it provides cheap, durable immutable history, snapshots, and time-travel semantics. CockroachDB for the rsync limitations at scale. \n\n## Authoritative token mapping and version datastore:\n\n| Field / Index | Datatype | Data type size | Description | Constrained / Indexed (true/false) |\n|---|---|---:|---|---|\n| map_id | UUID | 16 B | Caller-facing stable identifier (external identity) | true |\n| phi_record_id | UUID | 16 B | PHI store primary key (internal only) | true |\n| deid_token | UUID | 16 B | Non-derivable token for de-id store | true |\n| current_version | INT32 | 4 B | Latest committed version (monotonic authority) | false |\n| last_updated_at | INT32 | 4 B | Timestamp of last mutation (epoch or logical clock) | false |\n| last_event_id | INT32 | 4 B | Last event that advanced version | false |\n| last_persisted_version | INT32 | 4 B | Last version persisted to PHI (should equal current_version at COMMITTED) | false |\n| PK INDEX uq_map_id | btree on UUID | ~40 B/row (est.) | Unique index enforcing map_id uniqueness | — |\n| UNIQUE INDEX uq_phi_record_id | btree on UUID | ~40 B/row (est.) | Unique index enforcing phi_record_id uniqueness | — |\n| UNIQUE INDEX uq_deid_token | btree on UUID | ~40 B/row (est.) | Unique index enforcing deid_token uniqueness | — |\n||||||\n| **ESTIMATED ROW + INDEX FOOTPRINT** | — | ~184 B (est.) | Logical payload (~64 B) + 3×btree index entries (~40 B each) | — |\n\nSummary:\n- Logical payload size per mapping row (no DB overhead): 3×UUID (48 B) + 4×INT32 (16 B) ≈ 64 B.\n- Postgres storage will be larger due to tuple headers, alignment, and index overhead (often 2–3× the logical payload depending on fillfactor and vacuum).\n- Each UUID unique btree index entry is typically on the order of a few dozen bytes per row; the estimates above (~40 B/row) are for quick sizing and should be validated with real measurements (pg_relation_size) once data volume is known.\n\n## Event State Store State Model\n- QUEUED — mapping allocated (for creates) without version; request recorded for idempotency + replay\n            Note: For create requests, map_id is allocated at QUEUED and remains stable for the lifetime of the event_id. Retries of the same event_id return the same map_id\n- COMMITTED — authoritative mapping assigns version=v and PHI(v) is durably written (atomic phase-1)\n- DEID_PERSISTED (terminal) — de-id projection (v) written successfully\n- DEID_DLQ (terminal) — de-id projection failed beyond retry policy\n\n## Interfaces in scope\nWrite APIs (required)\n- Create patient: caller provides event_id, system returns 202 {event_id, map_id} immediately from the QUEUED allocation.\n    POST /api/v1/patient (create) → 202 {event_id, map_id, phase=\"QUEUED\"}        \n- Update patient: requires map_id + caller-provided event_id, returns 202.\n    PUT /api/v1/patient/{map_id} (update) → 202 {event_id, map_id, phase=\"QUEUED\"}           \nRead APIs (data queries)\n- GET /api/v1/deid/patients/{map_id} → latest de-id record (mapping→token→versioned read)\n- GET /api/v1/phi/patients/{map_id} → PHI record (privileged boundary; mocked)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "# Solution Doc for Performant, Reliable, Secure Real Time Writes\n\n## Mission\nWe are building a patient events platform for real-time ingestion, de-identify on write, and make de-identified records queryable within 5 seconds p99 while enforcing logical referential constraints to PHI data.\n\n## Invariants\n### Invariant: Global Idempotency by event_id\n\n    Guarantee: For any caller-provided event_id, the system returns the same outcome on retry: same map_id, same assigned version (once committed), and a monotonic phase transition (QUEUED→COMMITTED→DEID_PERSISTED/DEID_DLQ).\n    If the same event_id is presented with a different payload than originally queued, the request is rejected (e.g., 409) and does not mutate state.\n    \n### Invariant: Atomic Phase-1 Commit\n\n    Guarantee: Transition to COMMITTED(version=v) occurs if and only if:\n            1. the authoritative mapping row is durably written/updated with current_version=v and relevant metadata, and\n            2. PHI record (phi_record_id, v) is durably written (immutable). No partial COMMITTED is visible to callers.\n    \n### Invariant: Monotonic Version Authority & Serialization\n\n    Guarantee: For each map_id, versions strictly increase; version assignment defines ingest-time order and PHI state mutations are applied in that order.\n\n### Invariant: PHI Commit Before De-ID Projection\n\n    Guarantee: A de-id projection for (deid_token, version=v) must not be emitted unless the mapping store indicates COMMITTED(version=v) and the PHI record (phi_record_id, v) exists.\n    \n### Invariant: De-identification Separation\n\n    Guarantee: De-ID records contain no direct identifiers. Linkage to PHI is via deid_token and privileged resolution only. Tokens are not derivable from PHI fields.\n    \n### Invariant: Idempotent De-ID Projection (Downstream of COMMITTED)\n\n    Guarantee: Phase 2 de-identification is triggered only after Phase 1 is COMMITTED and uses the authoritative (deid_token, version) emitted by the atomic commit path. De-ID writes are idempotent by key (deid_token, version): retries must not create duplicates and must not overwrite an existing (deid_token, version) record.\n    \n### Invariant: Bounded De-ID Materialization\n\n    Guarantee: When de-id dependencies are healthy, DEID_PERSISTED is reached within 5 seconds p99 after admission / COMMITTED. Under degraded conditions, de-id materialization reaches DEID_PERSISTED within 15 minutes p99 after recovery; otherwise terminal DEID_DLQ is recorded.\n\n### Invariant: Long-Term PHI Version Retention\n\n    Guarantee: Because the PHI store is an authoritative system of record, all committed PHI versions (phi_record_id, version) are retained in immutable form for the legally required retention period (e.g., years), unless explicitly removed by a compliant erasure process (which is out-of-scope for this design).\n    \n\n## In-Scope\n- Ingest supports create + update workflows with caller-provided event_id\n- Idempotency by event_id with conflict detection on payload mismatch\n- Mapping/tokenization + version assignment as authoritative\n- Phase-1 atomic commit (mapping version + PHI immutable write)\n- Phase-2 de-id materialization with retry + DLQ terminal state\n- p99 ≤ 5s to reach DEID_PERSISTED in healthy conditions\n- Privileged PHI resolution via deid_token (interface can be mocked)\n\n## Out-of-scope\n- Control Plane vs Data Plane Separation\n- Authorization Boundaries\n- Audit & immutability guarantees beyond the versioned append-only model\n- Cost showback\n- Full observability platform (dashboards/alerts), aside from minimal phase timestamps if needed\n- Multi-region active/active\n- Deletes / erasure\n- Rich query APIs for business analytics (“API query of the data”)\n\n## Assumptions\n- Caller must provide a globally unique event_id for each semantic write. Retries must reuse the same event_id; event_id reuse across distinct payloads is a client bug and results in a deterministic 409 Conflict.\n- The SLO measures time from admission/commit to data visibility in the de-id read API. Query execution latency itself is out-of-scope except to the extent it must be negligible for key-based reads.\n- Prototype-only: simulate PHI separation, no real compliance claims(encryption, key mgmt, access controls, audit logs)\n- This is a single tenant, single region(w/ replication capabilities), separate data endpoints for PHI vs De-identification records.\n- “Queryable” for this take-home means the de-id record exists and is readable by key\n- 325M people in Epic system with EHR - this system should match in size\n- (1 kafka partition manages 600,000Kb/minute)/(20kb messages)=30,000 messages/minute per partition max\n- event_id reuse across distinct payloads is considered a client bug and results in a deterministic 409 Conflict.\n    \n\n## Deployment Technology Choices\n\n| Component | Take-Home / Rancher (Helm) | Production Direction |\n|---|---|---|\n| Event Topic `patient-events` | **Kafka Topic** default retention w/ one partition ISR=1 | **Kafka Topic** (multi-broker, multi-AZ, partitions=34, ISR=3, retention=24hours, 800GB max partition size)  |\n| `map-id-pool` queue (ID pool) | **Queues for Kafka** topic with retention kept simple for the prototype | **Queues for Kafka** with bounded retention by size and continuous pool replenishment |\n| Stream processing | **Flink** jobs (Phase 1 coordinator, Phase 2 projector) | **Flink** with HA(2 job managers, 2 task managers(6 core machines)), state backend, blue/green upgrades  |\n| Authoritative token mapping (Phase 1) | **PostgreSQL** (single-region) | **CockroachDB** (multi-region async replication, 60GB storage across 16 nodes) |\n| Immutable PHI store | **PostgreSQL** append-only table keyed by `(phi_record_id, version)` | **Object storage** (S3/MinIO + multi-region) + **Apache Iceberg** for immutable versioned history and time travel |\n| Immutable De-ID store | **PostgreSQL** append-only table keyed by `(deid_token, version)` | **Object storage** (S3/MinIO + multi-region) + **Apache Iceberg** (same rationale as PHI) |\n| DLQ | Kafka DLQ Topic | Kafka DLQ topic (34 partitions, 1GB/partition, 24hour retention, ISR=3) Must hold 24 hours of data or 64GB(color,  char(32)+deid_token, UUID(16b))/day but must also match partition count of ingestion topic. |\n\nNotes:\n- The take-home minimizes components by using PostgreSQL for immutable stores and Kafka for both the event queue and the `map_id` queue.\n- In production, Apache Iceberg on object storage is the preferred direction for the immutable stores because it provides cheap, durable immutable history, snapshots, and time-travel semantics. CockroachDB for the rsync limitations at scale. \n\n## Authoritative token mapping and version datastore:\n\n| Field / Index | Datatype | Data type size | Description | Constrained / Indexed (true/false) |\n|---|---|---:|---|---|\n| map_id | UUID | 16 B | Caller-facing stable identifier (external identity) | true |\n| phi_record_id | UUID | 16 B | PHI store primary key (internal only) | true |\n| deid_token | UUID | 16 B | Non-derivable token for de-id store | true |\n| current_version | INT32 | 4 B | Latest committed version (monotonic authority) | false |\n| last_updated_at | INT32 | 4 B | Timestamp of last mutation (epoch or logical clock) | false |\n| last_event_id | INT32 | 4 B | Last event that advanced version | false |\n| last_persisted_version | INT32 | 4 B | Last version persisted to PHI (should equal current_version at COMMITTED) | false |\n| PK INDEX uq_map_id | btree on UUID | ~40 B/row (est.) | Unique index enforcing map_id uniqueness | — |\n| UNIQUE INDEX uq_phi_record_id | btree on UUID | ~40 B/row (est.) | Unique index enforcing phi_record_id uniqueness | — |\n| UNIQUE INDEX uq_deid_token | btree on UUID | ~40 B/row (est.) | Unique index enforcing deid_token uniqueness | — |\n||||||\n| **ESTIMATED ROW + INDEX FOOTPRINT** | — | ~184 B (est.) | Logical payload (~64 B) + 3×btree index entries (~40 B each) | — |\n\nSummary:\n- Logical payload size per mapping row (no DB overhead): 3×UUID (48 B) + 4×INT32 (16 B) ≈ 64 B.\n- Postgres storage will be larger due to tuple headers, alignment, and index overhead (often 2–3× the logical payload depending on fillfactor and vacuum).\n- Each UUID unique btree index entry is typically on the order of a few dozen bytes per row; the estimates above (~40 B/row) are for quick sizing and should be validated with real measurements (pg_relation_size) once data volume is known.\n\n## Event State Store State Model\n- QUEUED — mapping allocated (for creates) without version; request recorded for idempotency + replay\n            Note: For create requests, map_id is allocated at QUEUED and remains stable for the lifetime of the event_id. Retries of the same event_id return the same map_id\n- COMMITTED — authoritative mapping assigns version=v and PHI(v) is durably written (atomic phase-1)\n- DEID_PERSISTED (terminal) — de-id projection (v) written successfully\n- DEID_DLQ (terminal) — de-id projection failed beyond retry policy\n\n## Interfaces in scope\nWrite APIs (required)\n- Create patient: caller provides event_id, system returns 202 {event_id, map_id} immediately from the QUEUED allocation.\n    POST /api/v1/patient (create) → 202 {event_id, map_id, phase=\"QUEUED\"}        \n- Update patient: requires map_id + caller-provided event_id, returns 202.\n    PUT /api/v1/patient/{map_id} (update) → 202 {event_id, map_id, phase=\"QUEUED\"}           \nRead APIs (data queries)\n- GET /api/v1/deid/patients/{map_id} → latest de-id record (mapping→token→versioned read)\n- GET /api/v1/phi/patients/{map_id} → PHI record (privileged boundary; mocked)",
